	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>New EU trade policy communication planned</h1>

			
			<h4>
												04 May 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The EC is planning a new communication on its trade policy later in 2010, to dovetail with the ‘Europe 2020 Strategy’. During a speech to a civil society trade seminar in Prague in March 2010, Trade Commissioner Karel De Gucht set out the elements to be included in the strategy: </p>
<ul>

<li>concluding the Doha Round;</li>

<li>concluding ongoing bilateral negotiations, with differentiation in the agreements concluded, based on the level of development of the partner country;</li>

<li>the inclusion of broader issues reaching beyond the traditional tariff agenda in future negotiations;</li>

<li>re-energising the Transatlantic Economic Council;</li>

<li>re-energising the High Level Economic and Trade Dialogue with China;</li>

<li>promoting ‘greener’ production and trade by putting in place ‘the right regulatory environment and international standards’;</li>

<li>continuing negotiations with the ACP to tailor agreements to ACP needs, and avoiding any ‘one size fits all’ approach;</li>

<li>revision of the GSP scheme to target preferences more on those countries that need them most;</li>

<li>an examination of how the EU’s new powers in the area of foreign direct investment can be used to expand opportunities for EU companies and better protect EU investments in third countries (a communication will be issued in late spring 2010).</li>

</ul>

		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
EC, DG Trade, speech by EC Trade Commissioner Karel De Gucht, 24 March 2010<br/>
<a href="http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2010/march/tradoc_145949.pdf" target="_self">http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2010/march/tradoc_145949.pdf</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>While the commitment to tailoring EPA agreements to the needs of ACP countries needs to be acknowledged as a way of moving the negotiations forward, it could however potentially throw up problems of regional harmonisation, given the diversity within ACP regions. This remains one of the basic challenges, particularly in Africa, where the majority of ACP countries are least developed, but lie in regions economically dominated by larger, more developed, economies.</p><p>The focus under the EC’s policy on bilateral trade agreements is increasingly likely to shift to those countries of greatest commercial interest to the EU. This could well accelerate the process of preference erosion faced by ACP exporters, although this will depend on the agricultural production patterns in the countries concerned and the precise nature of the tariff concession granted to these countries, in areas directly competitive with ACP exporters.</p><p>The commitment to ‘greener’ production through putting in place ‘the right regulatory environment and international standards’ could well lead to even stricter standards and regulatory requirements, which could be particularly disadvantageous to smaller ACP economies which may not be able to achieve the economies of scale necessary to make compliance commercially viable. </p><p>In some ACP countries, the EC’s commitment to the revision of the GSP scheme to target preferences more on those who most need them, could lead to calls for graduation out of LDC status. This could exert additional pressure on the governments of the countries affected to conclude economic partnership agreements (e.g. Angola). However it should be noted that the question of a country’s LDC status is a matter for the UN, and not primarily the EU. </p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

